    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>HD100546 is one of the very few discs where we witness presence of a planet as 
it shapes the regions it recently formed in. ALMA observations of HD100546 
will be of utmost importance in revealing details of disc-planet interactions, 
and setting the existing theories on a better path, providing the physical 
conditions and matter distribution for theoretical models. The bright disc 
around HD100546 has a well characterised gap observed with a myriad of 
state-of-art telescopes, but it's southern location kept it hidden from the 
eyes of submillimetre interferometers. We propose to image the gap around 
HD100546 at highest angular resolution offered in band 7, with the aim of 
measuring the distribution of millimetre sized particles around the gap for 
direct comparison with finer dust seen with polarimetric imaging and 
mid-infrared interferometry. Only ALMA can provide the direct images to test 
if asymmetries seen in the mid-IR are due to a mass flow, resonant modes, or a pressure 
vortex. A further comparison with the gas distribution will be a crucial piece 
of the puzzle that is currenly lacking in our sophisticated models.</prp:abstract>
